  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a001" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a001.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a001.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.1 — Is liberality a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a001-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q117-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">hat are without, such as the things of this world that are granted us for our livelihood. Wherefore since it belongs to liberality to use these things well, it follows that liberality is a virtue .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a002" target="concept.external_goods" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a002.treated_in.concept.external_goods">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a002.treated_in.concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.2 — What is its matter?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d12">External Goods</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a002-treated-in-concept-external-goods-st-ii-ii-q117-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ch are the subject of a man's free-handedness towards others are the goods he possesses, which are denoted by the term "money." Therefore the proper matter of liberality is money.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a002" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a002.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a002.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.2 — What is its matter?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a002-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q117-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">According to the Philosopher (Ethic. iv, 1) it belongs to the liberal man to part with things. Hence liberality is also called open-handedness [largitas], because that which is open does not withhold things but parts of them. The term "liberality" seems also to allude to</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a003" target="concept.external_goods" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a003.treated_in.concept.external_goods">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a003.treated_in.concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.3 — Its act</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d12">External Goods</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a003-treated-in-concept-external-goods-st-ii-ii-q117-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ce liberality is a virtue , its act is consistent with money. Now money comes under the head of useful goods, since all external goods are directed to man's use. Hence the proper act of liberality is making use of money or riches .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a003" target="concept.giving" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a003.treated_in.concept.giving">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a003.treated_in.concept.giving</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.3 — Its act</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.giving</data>
  <data key="d12">Giving</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a003-treated-in-concept-giving-st-ii-ii-q117-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The species of an act is taken from its object, as stated above ( I-II:18:2 ). Now the object or matter of liberality is money and whatever has a money value, as stated in the foregoing Article (Reply to Objection 2). And since every virtue is consistent with</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a003" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a003.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a003.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.3 — Its act</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a003-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q117-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The species of an act is taken from its object, as stated above ( I-II:18:2 ). Now the object or matter of liberality is money and whatever has a money value, as stated in the foregoing Article (Reply to Objection 2). And since every virtue is consistent with its object, it fo</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a004" target="concept.giving" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a004.treated_in.concept.giving">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a004.treated_in.concept.giving</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.4 — Does it pertain thereto to give rather than to take?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.giving</data>
  <data key="d12">Giving</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a004-treated-in-concept-giving-st-ii-ii-q117-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">when we throw something—the farther we put it away the greater the force [virtus] employed. Hence parting with money by giving it to others proceeds from a greater virtue than when we spend it on ourselves. But it is proper to a virtue as such to tend to what is more perfect, since " v</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a004" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a004.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a004.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.4 — Does it pertain thereto to give rather than to take?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a004-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q117-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">It is proper to a liberal man to use money. Now the use of money consists in parting with it. For the acquisition of money is like generation rather than use: while the keeping of money, in so far as it is directed to facilitate the use of money, is like a hab</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a005" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a005.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a005.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.5 — Is liberality a part of justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a005-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q117-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Liberality is not a species of justice , since justice pays another what is his whereas liberality gives another what is one's own. There are, however, two points in which it agrees with justice : f</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a005" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a005.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a005.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.5 — Is liberality a part of justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a005-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q117-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Liberality is not a species of justice , since justice pays another what is his whereas liberality gives another what is one's own. There are, however, two points in whic</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a006" target="concept.external_goods" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a006.treated_in.concept.external_goods">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a006.treated_in.concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.6 — Its comparison with other virtues</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d12">External Goods</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a006-treated-in-concept-external-goods-st-ii-ii-q117-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">uently. Primarily and of its very nature it tends to set in order one's own affection towards the possession and use of money. On this way temperance , which moderates desires and pleasures relating to one's own body, takes precedence of liberality: and so do fortitude and justice , w</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q117.a006" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a006.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q117.a006.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q117.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.117 a.6 — Its comparison with other virtues</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q117-a006-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q117-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q117.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Every virtue tends towards a good ; wherefore the greater virtue is that which tends towards the greater good . Now liberality tends towards a good in two ways: in one way, primarily and of its own nature ; in another way, consequently. Primarily and of its very nature it tends to set</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 — The vices opposed to liberality, and in the first place, of covetousness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">will be a sin for him to exceed this measure, by wishing to acquire or keep them immoderately. This is what is meant by covetousness , which is defined as "immoderate love of possessing." It is therefore evident that covetousness is a sin .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118" target="concept.external_goods" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.external_goods">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 — The vices opposed to liberality, and in the first place, of covetousness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d12">External Goods</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-treated-in-concept-external-goods-st-ii-ii-q118-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">surate with the end, as, for instance, medicine is commensurate with health, as the Philosopher observes (Polit. i, 6). External goods come under the head of things useful for an end, as stated above ( II-II:117:3 ; I-II:02:1 ). Hence it must needs be that man's good in their respect consists</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 — The vices opposed to liberality, and in the first place, of covetousness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q118-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">In whatever things good consists in a due measure, evil must of necessity ensue through excess or deficiency of that measure. Now in all things that are for an end, the good consists in a certain measure: since whatever is directed to an end must needs be comm</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118" target="concept.retaining" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.retaining">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.treated_in.concept.retaining</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 — The vices opposed to liberality, and in the first place, of covetousness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.retaining</data>
  <data key="d12">Retaining</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-treated-in-concept-retaining-st-ii-ii-q118-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">man seeks, according to a certain measure, to have external riches , in so far as they are necessary for him to live in keeping with his condition of life. Wherefore it will be a sin for him to exceed this measure, by wishing to acquire or keep them immoderately. This is what is meant b</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
