<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a001" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a001.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a001.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.1 — Is covetousness a sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a001-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">will be a sin for him to exceed this measure, by wishing to acquire or keep them immoderately. This is what is meant by covetousness , which is defined as "immoderate love of possessing." It is therefore evident that covetousness is a sin .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a001" target="concept.external_goods" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a001.treated_in.concept.external_goods">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a001.treated_in.concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.1 — Is covetousness a sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d12">External Goods</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a001-treated-in-concept-external-goods-st-ii-ii-q118-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">surate with the end, as, for instance, medicine is commensurate with health, as the Philosopher observes (Polit. i, 6). External goods come under the head of things useful for an end, as stated above ( II-II:117:3 ; I-II:02:1 ). Hence it must needs be that man's good in their respect consists</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a002" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a002.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a002.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.2 — Is it a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a002-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">uch, come under the head of useful good , since they are desired under the aspect of being useful to man . Consequently covetousness is a special sin , forasmuch as it is an immoderate love of having possessions, which are comprised under the name of money, whence covetousness [avaritia] is</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a002" target="concept.external_goods" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a002.treated_in.concept.external_goods">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a002.treated_in.concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.2 — Is it a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d12">External Goods</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a002-treated-in-concept-external-goods-st-ii-ii-q118-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">s is a special sin , forasmuch as it is an immoderate love of having possessions, which are comprised under the name of money, whence covetousness [avaritia] is denominated. Since, however, the verb "to have," which seems to have been originally employed in connection with possessions</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a003" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a003.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a003.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.3 — To which virtue it is opposed</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a003-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Covetousness denotes immoderation with regard to riches in two ways. First, immediately in respect of the acquisition and keeping of riches . On this way a man obtains mone</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a003" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a003.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a003.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.3 — To which virtue it is opposed</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a003-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q118-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">too much, or takes too much pleasure in them, even if he be unwilling to steal. On this way covetousness is opposed to liberality, which moderates these affections, as stated above ( 117, 2, ad 3, 3, ad 3, 6 ). On this sense covetousness is spoken of ( 2 Corinthians 9:5 ): "That they woul</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a003" target="concept.retaining" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a003.treated_in.concept.retaining">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a003.treated_in.concept.retaining</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.3 — To which virtue it is opposed</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.retaining</data>
  <data key="d12">Retaining</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a003-treated-in-concept-retaining-st-ii-ii-q118-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ly in respect of the acquisition and keeping of riches . On this way a man obtains money beyond his due, by stealing or retaining another's property. This is opposed to justice , and in this sense covetousness is mentioned ( Ezekiel 22:27 ): "Her princes in the midst of her are like wolve</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a004" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a004.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a004.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.4 — Is it a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a004-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 3 ) covetousness is twofold. On one way it is opposed to justice , and thus it is a mortal sin in respect of its genus. For in this sense covetousness consists in the unjust ta</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a005" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a005.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a005.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.5 — Is it the most grievous of sins?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a005-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">erson , and after this comes a sin against external things, which are deputed to man's use, and this seems to belong to covetousness . Secondly, the degrees of sin may be considered on the part of the good to which the human appetite is inordinately subjected; and then the lesser the good ,</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a006" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a006.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a006.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.6 — Is it a sin of the flesh or a spiritual sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a006-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">arnal pleasures, while spiritual sins are consummated in pleasures of the spirit without pleasure of the flesh. Such is covetousness : for the covetous man takes pleasure in the consideration of himself as a possessor of riches . Therefore covetousness is a spiritual sin .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a007" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a007.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a007.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.7 — Is it a capital vice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a007-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">of taking possession of something," and again it is written ( Ecclesiastes 10:19 ): "All things obey money." Therefore covetousness , which is desire for money, is a capital vice .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q118.a008" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a008.treated_in.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q118.a008.treated_in.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q118.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.118 a.8 — Its daughters</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d12">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q118-a008-treated-in-concept-covetousness-st-ii-ii-q118-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q118.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The daughters of covetousness are the vices which arise therefrom, especially in respect of the desire of an end. Now since covetousness is excessive love of possessing riches , it exceeds</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q119" target="concept.external_goods" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.external_goods">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q119</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.119 — Prodigality</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.external_goods</data>
  <data key="d12">External Goods</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q119-treated-in-concept-external-goods-st-ii-ii-q119-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q119.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">. Now covetousness and prodigality differ variously in respect of excess and deficiency. Thus, as regards affection for riches , the covetous man exceeds by loving them more than he ought, while the prodigal is deficient, by being less careful of them than he ought: and as regards exte</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q119" target="concept.giving" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.giving">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.giving</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q119</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.119 — Prodigality</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.giving</data>
  <data key="d12">Giving</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q119-treated-in-concept-giving-st-ii-ii-q119-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q119.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">s deficient, by being less careful of them than he ought: and as regards external action, prodigality implies excess in giving, but deficiency in retaining and acquiring, while covetousness , on the contrary, denotes deficiency in giving, but excess in acquiring and retaining. Hence it</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q119" target="concept.liberality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.liberality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q119</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.119 — Prodigality</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.liberality</data>
  <data key="d12">Liberality</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q119-treated-in-concept-liberality-st-ii-ii-q119-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q119.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">In morals vices are opposed to one another and to virtue in respect of excess and deficiency. Now covetousness and prodigality differ variously in respect of excess and deficiency. Thus, as regards affection for riches , the covetous man exceeds by loving them</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">external_goods</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q119" target="concept.prodigality" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.prodigality">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q119.treated_in.concept.prodigality</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q119</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.119 — Prodigality</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prodigality</data>
  <data key="d12">Prodigality</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
